  "datePublished": "2026-04-02",
  "description": "Perennial herb from Ranunculaceae, native to high-altitude Rocky Mountain meadows (Colorado, Montana, New Mexico, Utah). Hardy zones 3-9. Flowers bear distinctive backwardly-projecting spurs arising from modified sepals; sepals blue or pale, petals white, spurs prominent and nectar-bearing. Blooms year two from seed. Critical early-season nectar source for native bumblebees (Bombus) and long-tongued bees (Anthophora, Eucera); also visited by hummingbirds. Self-seeds readily in cultivation.",
  "name": "Aquilegia caerulea",
